[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## What the Recipe Gets Right
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The Problem section is the strongest opening in Chapter 7.** The care manager scenario is specific, relatable, and immediately communicates why timing matters beyond risk scoring. "Call too early, and the patient isn't ready to engage... Call too late, and the patient is already in the ED with DKA" is a perfect encapsulation of the problem. The $15,000 hospitalization vs. $50 phone call framing makes the business case without being salesy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The Technology section is genuinely educational.** The progression from static risk scores to hazard functions to dynamic survival models to counterfactual timing is well-structured. The explanation of why Cox proportional hazards is a "terrible assumption for healthcare" (because covariate effects change over time) is clinically correct and will save readers from a common modeling mistake. The three architecture families (RNN, Transformer, Counterfactual) are accurately described with appropriate caveats.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The causal inference discussion is honest about what's hard.** The recipe doesn't pretend that IPTW or G-computation are easy to implement. The recommendation to "save the full causal/RL approach for when you have the data volume and the organizational maturity to validate it properly" is exactly the right advice for most healthcare organizations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The "What Makes Timing Prediction Uniquely Hard" subsection is excellent.** Sparse positive events, irregular observation intervals, heterogeneous intervention effects, and the self-fulfilling prophecy problem are all real challenges that would take a team months to discover independently. Calling these out upfront saves readers from building systems that fail for predictable reasons.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The pseudocode is well-structured and accessible.** Each step has a clear business explanation, a "what goes wrong if you skip it" note, and code that a non-developer can follow. The temporal feature engineering (Step 2) is particularly good: medication gap days, encounter acceleration, and intervention fatigue dampening are all clinically meaningful features that demonstrate the difference between static and dynamic risk assessment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The "Honest Take" is the best in the chapter.** The admission that "most organizations end up building a really good risk score and calling it a timing model" is refreshingly honest. The intervention fatigue insight ("if you call a patient every week because your model keeps flagging them, they stop answering") is a real-world lesson that most ML papers ignore. The pragmatic advice to start with the hybrid approach and only invest in causal/RL when you have the data and maturity is exactly right.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The Variations section adds genuine value.** Multi-intervention timing, channel-aware scheduling, and outcome-driven retraining with causal correction are all natural extensions that give readers a roadmap for increasing sophistication over time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
